values:
In Central Oregon October 4th is the official start of winter (at least this year).
Most of the leaves are still on the trees, and this is particularly heavy wet snow, so we've some broken tree limbs. The first hard freeze was a week ago, so the greenhouse has already been shut down and the tomatoes are safe inside.

We've a new family member here at the Beyer household. His name is Tucker and he's a West Highland White Terrier and is 8 weeks old and 4 pounds, 10 ounces. My recently-retired father will he his custodian in several senses of the word.

Life on the West Coast... is good! The family was in Portland last weekend for a juggling festival and came home via Hood River where we acquired fresh apples. Today I made an apple pie using some of the aforementioned apples. As you can see, it is delicious. (There are five slices left... for now) To my own amazement I discovered I didn't have the new Lego microcomputer/servo motor set. Amazon fixed the problem and I'm currently fiddling around with basic models marveling at how well the ultrasonic distance sensor works. Bumping into walls (to trigger a touch sensor) may be a thing of the past. No what-have-I-been-doing-for-the-last-four-months entry would be complete without the mention of toe shoes. Vibram Five Fingers are the best fitting, most comfortable shoes I've owned. They're also the most commented-on shoes I've ever owned. The joy of wearing them even makes up for the need to tell people where I got them. The cell phone in my pocket isn't as foreign as it was last post, and I'm well on my way using half of my 1K minutes in a year.

It's a wonderful winter we're having in central Oregon. I went skate skiing today for ~16 km on the Pole Pedal Paddle course. The snow was slightly soft and the temperature above freezing, but it was still an amazing ski considering... it's MAY. The bus had stopped at at the top of Government Camp pass (as scheduled) as I rode home from Portland last Sunday and a police officer got on the bus, came over to me, and asked to see some ID. Having not heard the phrase "papers please" in America before I asked why, and the officer said he'd tell me afterwards. I briefly considered refusing, but the benefits did not seem to outweigh the risks, so I handed over my drivers license. The officer looked at it for a second, handed it back, said something about looking for someone, and left. The most frightening thing concerning this is my ignorance regarding my rights. I'd assume that I could refuse to provide ID (4th amendment style) but in sixteen years of schooling the topic has never been covered and I'm not sure where I'd find a non-legalese summary of the law. Has anyone else been asked apparently at random to produce ID in America? I beat Half Life II yesterday. Now I've got to decide if I should try Eve (as pressured by co-workers) or press on to HL2 Episode I. If anyone has not read Nick Bostrom's, Where Are They? Why I hope the search for extraterrestrial life finds nothing. I recommend it. I don't entirely agree with the logic behind the argument, but it's an interesting take on the matter.

The opportunity cost of visiting will decrease (for those of you who live in Washington) on the 25th and 26th as a Powell's pilgrimage is scheduled for that weekend.  If anyone else wants to hang out in one of the largest bookstores in the US and play Ticket to Ride into the wee hours of the night, let me know.

Portal is a great game.  
(I suspect the majority of people reading this have already come to this realization.)
[I keep trying to open portals in firefox.]
Werd

My brother just sent me an email pondering the possible presence of other Bend-ites over Christmas.  I was about to reply saying <lj user= rc_cola> and Zack where scheduled to return, and that I hadn't heard from anyone else, when it occurred to me that I could just post the question.

So, who's coming back to Bend over Christmas?

Snow!
There were two inches in town today when I woke up, and I've heard that the mountains had nearly a foot of snow and were expecting more.  Skiing season is soon to be upon Bend.
Hurrah!

Status:
House-and-dog sitting for some friends who have left me with a digital projector and surround sound enabled entertainment center, a 36 pack of Dr. Pepper, guacamole, corn chips, and jellybeans (some of which I've already managed to share).  Additionally I have obtained a bag of ambrosia disguised as molasses cookies (<lj user= rc_cola> will understand).
I'm house-sitting till Sunday and have not yet watched anything, or opened the chips or guacamole.

Question:
What movie, group of movies, or series shall I acquire and watch this weekend?  

(Special bonus points are awarded to the suggestions of those who wish to join the party (I'm looking at you <lj user= lornelover>))

PS: hurrah for post-blood-donation lethargy

Only one post-interview reply expected now. *crosses fingers* *thinks* *looks for more interviews*

"Additionally, when you open, preview or click on the advertising portion of our e-mails and/or those of our marketing partners and/or affiliates of WorldwideBuffet, you have agreed to the terms set forth in our Privacy Policy and agree that as a function of opening, previewing or clicking on the advertising portion of our e-mails, that you will receive new or additional marketing communications from us, our marketing partners and/or affiliates of WorldwideBuffet."
-http://www.printbuffet.com/p.html

Who'd have guessed that I could agree to a privacy policy (which says you have no privacy) merely by opening an email?  Shocking.  Perhaps I can (from a new and temporary email account) send them an email that mirrors theirs and has a privacy policy of 'send me money.'  Come to think of it, that's likely a mirror to their business practices as well.

Ah well, another day, another interview.  Now I've two businesses that I have both interviewed at and not yet heard back from. 
*crosses fingers*

Finally, I've read all the Sandman that I've seen at the public library, leaving me hunting/reserving volumes 2, 3 and 8.  I can not be at peace until I have read them.

I really should track down the last two or three episodes that I've not yet watched; it's hard to call firefly my second favorite TV show (Futurama is first) when I've not yet watched all of it.

Back in Bend!
	I flew into Redmond successfully (the plane was only 15 minutes late), met up with my parents, and made it home.  We went out for lunch at the Pilot Butte Drive Through (the greatest burger joint in town, perhaps anywhere.  Then I slept for 18 hours.  Now I have big plans on biking downtown (when the bank opens) and depositing birthday money and trying to meet up with friends who are in town.
